 Its reasons are as follows: Extracted preferences and dislikes (from my self‑introduction): I prefer alternative/new‑wave/post‑punk characteristics — angular guitars, propulsive, slightly off‑kilter rhythms, layered synth textures and moody, intimate vocal delivery. I value production that creates space, tension and sonic character rather than polishing everything flat; careful mastering and pressings that preserve dynamic nuance; albums whose songs have distinct identities, reveal details on repeat listens, and sustain a cohesive mood that rewards full‑disc play. I retain a liking for emotional grit, strong songwriting and clear instrument separation. I explicitly dislike over‑polished arena‑AOR formulae and glossy “greatest hits” homogenization — bombastic, interchangeable choruses or production that flattens dynamics and erases individual performance character — and I avoid releases that favor safety and sheen over textural interest and individuality.
Evaluation and decision: The Textured New Wave/post‑punk set aligns closely with virtually every item in my preference list: it features angular guitars, propulsive off‑kilter rhythms, layered synths and moody, intimate vocals; its production is described as spacious and tension‑driven with careful mastering that preserves dynamic nuance; songs have distinct identities and the release rewards full‑disc, repeat listening for listeners who favour grit and textural interest. Those are direct matches to my stated tastes (genre, instrumental textures, production philosophy, and album‑scale cohesion).
By contrast, Journey: Greatest Hits, while offering clear instrument separation, warm analog tonality and tight sequencing, is a single‑disc AOR hits compilation built around immediate melodic hooks and arena‑ready sing‑along choruses. Those features run into my stated dislikes: the greatest‑hits single‑disc format and punchy, upfront mixes encourage immediate, surface‑level consumption rather than revealing new details on repeat listens; the arena sing‑along choruses and polished AOR approach embody the “bombastic/interchangeable chorus” and glossy homogenization I avoid. Although Journey does satisfy some technical preferences (clear separation, consistent mastering), those attributes are paired with production and songcraft that prioritize crowd‑pleasing immediacy and sheen over the textured, tension‑driven individuality I seek.
Conclusion: Because the Textured New Wave/post‑punk set matches my core sonic and production preferences (angular instrumentation, off‑kilter rhythms, layered synths, intimate vocals, spacious/tensioned production and careful mastering that preserves nuance and rewards album listening) and Journey’s greatest‑hits AOR format conflicts with my explicit dislikes (over‑polish, bombastic sing‑along choruses, compilation homogenization), I choose the Textured New Wave/post‑punk set and reject Journey: Greatest Hits.

